@@aTEMPLAR@@W

Templars are the oathforged convergence of @@aPaladin@@W resolve and @@aPriest@@W
devotion. They are front-line hierophants: part battle-cleric, part relentless
warding engine, sustaining allies while grinding down darkness with holy force.

To become a Templar, you follow the adept path tied to @@aPaladin@@W and
@@aPriest@@W remort progression.

@@aPassive class advantages@@W
Templar grants always-on scaling as adept levels rise:

  1) @@wPhysical damage bonus@@W
     - Your physical damage gains a passive Templar multiplier.
     - Scaling: +1% physical damage per Templar adept level (up to +20% at 20).

  2) @@wHoly damage bonus@@W
     - Holy-element attacks gain additional damage from Templar level.
     - Scaling: +2% holy damage per Templar adept level (up to +40% at 20).

  3) @@wHealing output bonus@@W
     - Healing spells and effects are strengthened by Templar level.
     - Scaling: +4% healing per Templar adept level (up to +80% at 20).

  4) @@wSpell critical damage bonus@@W
     - Templar adds passive spell critical multiplier scaling with Wisdom.

  5) @@wExtra attack round@@W
     - Having any Templar adept level grants an additional melee hit in the
       multi-hit calculation.

@@aUnique Templar mechanics@@W
  * @@wTemplar stance@@W becomes available with the adept path.
  * @@wEnhanced Heal@@W is learned at Templar level 1.
  * Casting @@wheal@@W as a Templar also attempts @@wcure blindness@@W,
    @@wremove curse@@W, and @@wcure poison@@W on the target.
  * Templar contributes to the @@wHoly Power@@W progression family.
  * Templar uses @@wWisdom@@W as its adept prime attribute.

@@aTemplar reincarnation bonuses@@W
Each Templar adept reincarnation grants passive scaling:

  * @@wHoly damage@@W: +2% per Templar adept reincarnation.
  * @@wPhysical damage@@W: +1% per Templar adept reincarnation.
  * @@wHealing output@@W: +1% per Templar adept reincarnation.

In short: Templar is the holy sustain adept—blending strong healing throughput,
status-cleansing utility, and reliable holy/physical pressure in one class.

